faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate concrete for a slab?"
    a: "Multiply slab length by width by thickness. This calculator converts thickness from inches to feet and estimates cubic feet, cubic yards, bags, and cost."
  - q: "How many cubic feet are in a cubic yard of concrete?"
    a: "There are 27 cubic feet in one cubic yard. Ready-mix concrete is commonly ordered by the cubic yard."
  - q: "How many bags of concrete do I need?"
    a: "Bag count depends on the total volume needed and the bag's cubic-foot yield. Enter the yield printed on your bag for the most accurate estimate."
  - q: "What is the yield of an 80 lb bag of concrete?"
    a: "Many 80 lb bags yield about 0.6 cubic feet, but you should check the specific bag label because yield can vary by product."
  - q: "How thick should a concrete slab be?"
    a: "Many light-duty residential slabs are around 4 inches thick, but the right thickness depends on load, use, soil, reinforcement, and local requirements."
  - q: "How much concrete do I need for fence post holes?"
    a: "Post hole concrete is based on the volume of a cylinder: hole diameter, hole depth, and number of holes. The post itself may displace some volume, so estimates can vary."
  - q: "Should I order extra concrete?"
    a: "Yes. A 5–10% overage helps account for uneven excavation, form variation, waste, and small measuring differences."
  - q: "When should I use ready-mix instead of bags?"
    a: "Ready-mix may be more practical for larger projects. Bagged concrete is often better for small slabs, repairs, footings, or post holes."
  - q: "Does this calculator account for rebar or wire mesh?"
    a: "No. This calculator estimates concrete volume only. Reinforcement needs depend on the project, load, local code, and professional guidance."
  - q: "Can I use this for footings?"
    a: "Yes, the concrete calculator includes a continuous footing option. Make sure footing dimensions meet project needs and local requirements."
